## SERP ANALYSIS

> **Blog Gen instruction:** Use competitor gaps — not what they cover — to drive structure and differentiation.

### Competitor Summary

**Common H2 topics competitors use (baseline — do not copy):**
- What are lavender nails / what colour is lavender
- Lavender nail ideas / inspiration gallery
- Lavender nail designs (marble, chrome, jelly, aura, floral)
- Best lavender nail polishes to buy
- How to do lavender nails at home
- Lavender nails meaning / symbolism
- Lavender nails for different nail lengths
- Celebrity lavender nails (Selena Gomez, Taylor Swift Lavender Haze tie-in)
- Lavender for summer vs. other seasons

**Competitor content approach:** Most top-ranking posts are inspiration galleries with minimal editorial depth, or surface-level "what is lavender" explainers. The Taylor Swift Lavender Haze tie-in appears everywhere but adds little practical value. Skin tone guidance, when present, stops at "suits cool undertones" with no further nuance — particularly for warm and olive skin, where the guidance is essentially missing. Nobody addresses the single most important tension: *lavender is called universally flattering, but it genuinely doesn't work equally well on all undertones — and the fix (shift from cool lavender to a warmer lilac) is never explained.*

**Visual patterns:** 8–15 images in most top results, heavy on artistic/editorial nail close-ups, very light on skin-tone demonstration or contextual outfit imagery.

**Recommended image count:** 8–10 images — at minimum one per skin tone section and one per finish option, plus outfit context shot. Informational posts live or die on "I can see myself in this" imagery.

### Competitor Gaps (Our Opportunity)

**Unanswered questions competitors are NOT answering:**
- Why lavender doesn't automatically "suit everyone" — and what to do if your undertone is warm or olive (shift to lilac, not pale lavender)
- What the actual difference is between lavender, lilac, periwinkle, and smoky lavender — and which one to buy for summer specifically
- Which finish to choose based on occasion: sheer jelly for daytime, chrome for events, matte for office, opaque for evening
- What outfits lavender pairs with in summer beyond the vague "white and linen" — real summer wardrobe logic
- Whether lavender holds up visually in sunlight and tan-skin conditions, or whether it washes out
- How lavender behaves on short nails (most imagery is on long almond/coffin)
- The smoky/grey-based lavender trend specifically (nail pros are calling it the "new neutral" for 2026 — this is completely absent from gallery posts)

**Missing semantic territory:**
- Smoky lavender / muted grey lavender as a neutral alternative to nude
- Lavender chrome as an upgrade path from flat lavender
- Warm-undertone-specific lavender guidance (warmer lilac vs. cool blue-lavender)
- Deep skin + saturated lavender vs. pale lavender distinction
- Summer outfit pairings with specificity beyond "white and pastels"
- Nail shape performance breakdown (almond vs squoval vs oval for lavender)

**Audience blind spots:**
- Readers don't know there are *different lavenders* — blue-based vs. pink-based vs. grey-based — and that these perform completely differently across skin tones
- The "it suits everyone" claim creates a false sense that any lavender polish works — when the shade selection matters enormously
- Nobody explains that lavender can read "bridal" rather than "summer" if you pick the wrong version or finish

### Our Strategic Approach

**Differentiation:** Own the shade-selection intelligence that competitors skip — the specific breakdown of which *type* of lavender (cool blue, warm lilac, smoky grey) works for which undertone and occasion. This is the gap that turns a browsing reader into a buyer.

**Structure plan:** Lead with the shade distinction (this is where we win immediately), then skin tone guide with specific shade-direction logic, then finish options mapped to occasions, then outfit pairings with summer specificity, then nail shapes, then products.

**Tone direction:** Knowledgeable but approachable — the tone of a beauty editor who won't waste your time with soft preamble; warm enough that readers feel seen rather than lectured.

